findings.description:
The symlink resolution in resource-copier.ts has a potential escape vector:

Code (lines 128-154):
```typescript
let canonicalPath = normalized;
if (fs.existsSync(normalized)) {
  try {
    canonicalPath = fs.realpathSync(normalized);  // Resolve symlinks
    // Verify canonical path still within root
    const canonicalNormalized = path.normalize(canonicalPath);
    if (!canonicalNormalized.startsWith(normalizedRoot + path.sep) && ...) {
      throw new Error(`Symlink escape detected...`);
    }
  } catch (err) {
    if ((err as Error).message.includes('Symlink escape')) {
      throw err;  // Re-throw escape errors
    }
    // Fall through to normalized path  // ← VULNERABILITY
  }
} else {
  canonicalPath = normalized;  // ← Non-existent paths bypass symlink check
}
```

TWO issues:
1. If realpathSync() throws (permission denied, I/O error), code falls through and uses unverified normalized path
2. If path doesn't exist yet (new project), canonicalPath is set to normalized without symlink check

Attack: Attacker can create symlink pointing outside root → code sees it doesn't exist yet → skips symlink check → uses normalized path as-is.

findings.recommendation:
1. Always attempt realpathSync() and fail on error (don't fall through):
```typescript
let canonicalPath = normalized;
if (fs.existsSync(normalized)) {
  try {
    canonicalPath = fs.realpathSync(normalized);
    // Verify canonical path
  } catch (err) {
    throw new Error(`Cannot resolve symlinks for ${normalized}: ${(err as Error).message}`);
  }
} else {
  // For non-existent paths, use normalized + startsWith check
  canonicalPath = normalized;
}
```
2. Test with: `ln -s /tmp/escape /projects/trap && copyToTarget('trap')`
3. Verify that non-existent paths still enforce startsWith check

findings.description:
The cursor cleanup logic runs on every cursor generation but may not be sufficient under heavy load:

Code (lines 108-125):
```typescript
function generateCursor(index: number, projectId?: string): string {
  const cursorId = Math.random().toString(36).slice(2);
  cursorMap.set(cursorId, { ... });

  // Cleanup old cursors (>24h)
  for (const [id, state] of cursorMap.entries()) {
    if (Date.now() - state.timestamp > 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000) {
      cursorMap.delete(id);
    }
  }

  return cursorId;
}
```

Issues:
1. Cleanup runs O(N) time where N = total cursors in map. On each cursor generation, iterates entire map.
2. No upper bound on map size. If cleanup is disabled or runs before 24h, map grows unbounded.
3. Each cursor stores: version (string), eventIndex (number), timestamp (number), projectId (string) ≈ 100+ bytes per cursor
4. At 1000 requests/sec → 86.4M cursors per day → 8.6GB memory per day

Example: System running for 1 week without restart:
- 604.8B requests × 100 bytes = 60GB memory (if all cursors are kept)

findings.recommendation:
1. Implement LRU eviction with hard cap:
```typescript
const CURSOR_MAX_SIZE = 100000; // Max cursors in memory
const CURSOR_TTL_MS = 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000; // 24h

if (cursorMap.size > CURSOR_MAX_SIZE) {
  // Find and remove oldest cursor
  let oldest = null, oldestAge = 0;
  for (const [id, state] of cursorMap.entries()) {
    const age = Date.now() - state.timestamp;
    if (age > oldestAge) {
      oldest = id;
      oldestAge = age;
    }
  }
  if (oldest) cursorMap.delete(oldest);
}
```
2. Use a priority queue (heap) for O(1) removal instead of O(N) scan
3. Add metrics: cursor count, max size reached, evictions
4. Test with 100K concurrent cursor generation → verify memory usage

